text.text:
Veganism is here to stay whether you like it or not. Veganism will not accept your condescending tone. It will not make you look five pounds thinner, it will not go better with coke, it will not be televised. 

Or maybe it will. All we know is there is some sense to it all, and some real good munching to be had, too. Whether you're a flexitarian, participating in Veganuary, or stay meat-free year round, it's nice to know that you can indulge in your favourite comfort foods without compromising your morals.

tip.text:
Chicken shops are a dime a dozen in London, but there's one newcomer that's cornered a fresh angle - House of Hackney (used to be called House of Seitan), with their vegan fried chicken and classic chip shop sides, completely blew up social media as they opened their doors for hoards of hungry herbivores.

Cheekily situated next to a butcher's shop (and with queues that put that butcher's shop to shame), the Seitan "chicken" lives up to the real thing, albeit much more bird friendly (and a little pricier) than your OG chicken and chips. Whether you're a flexitarian, participating in Veganuary, or stay meat-free year round, it's nice to know that you can now indulge in your favourite comfort food without compromising your morals.

address.line1: 41, Rye Lane Indoor Market, 48 Rye Ln

tip.text:
This vegan rastarant (their joke, not ours) feels very much part of Peckham. Owned by local legend Jahson Peat - who also runs a collection of eclectic African antique shops - Zionly is tucked into Rye Lane Market and every bit as idiosyncratic as its owner.

This is no hipster vegan joint: Peat's ethos comes from the Rastafarian mantra 'Eat not flesh' and a desire to bring healthy, mindful food to the community in which he was raised. With tasty, cheap, locally sourced vegan chow, we'd say he's been pretty successful in his mission. Pop by for some curry, dumplings, and a lengthy chat about all things Peckham.

tip.text:
Owned by the enigmatic King Cook, this London Fields spot is a favourite of grime outfit Boy Better Know with JME a regular fixture. King Cook's taken a millennial approach to veganism, with no preachy, dreadlocked crusties on site and a menu perfect for meat eaters and vegans alike. There's a dish called High Grade - a bowl of hemp oil stir-fried veggies in sweet and sour BBQ sauce, topped with green herbs and hemp seed crumbles - which should tell you all you need to know.

The menu is mostly taken up by creamy Thai curries and gingery noodle dishes, with a few nods to multicultural London: there's a tofu scramble full English, a few Jamaican goodies, a Yoga Fire (turmeric dahl), and a provencal garlicky, herby, truffle oil number too. Further up the scale of healthiness than a lot of East London vegan fast-food spots, a lot more delish' and with 100% more street cred; we've got a lotta time for Cook Daily.

tip.text:
Is the rapid spread of the 'small, sharing plates' trend doing your nut in? Well what better way to revolt than by getting rid of plates all together? Andu is the perfect spot to do so - this Kingsland Road gem is one of those no-bullshit places that serves up simple and delicious Ethiopian food which also happens to be 100% vegan. It's BYOB, the staff are bloody lovely and its damn cheap to boot. And as is the way with Ethiopian cuisine, the food is served atop injera bread (sour fermented pancake).

Wed recommend grabbing a pal and rolling down to Dalston to try the sampler, a selection of six dishes served atop injera or rice - perfect for two to share and yours for only 12. If youre in the area and dining Han Solo, you can get an individual sampler to take away for a fiver. So leave any vibe-snipers at home and get yourself down to Andu before you can say yemisir wot (Ethiopian red lentil stew).

tip.text:
Come get your moosh on at Mooshies, where the living is easy and the burgers are cruelty-free. This burger joint on Brick Lane dishes out all sorts of dutty hangover cures for London's growing vegan population and their curious carnivorous friends.

We went for a 'what's your beef' burger made from quinoa and black bean with caramelised onions, vegan cheese, gherkins and lettuce, but we'd be lying if we said the fillet-om-phish with battered aubergine, tartar sauce and nori seaweed didn't look delicious, too. Pair that with some crispy aubergine slices and a matcha brownie, then go tell all your meat-eating friends that they're stupid - friends love that kind of patronising shit.

text.text:
This burger joint on Brick Lane dishes out all sorts of dutty hangover cures for London's growing vegan population and their curious carnivorous friends. 

Check out this pulled jackfruit burger with BBQ sauce and coleslaw. Apparently jackfruit is the future, but if that's not your bag, the fillet-om-phish with battered aubergine, tartar sauce and nori seaweed is a great fish alternative.

tip.text:
This vegan pub puts up a tough guy front, but its just a big ol softie when it really comes down to it. From the same guys behind Deptford mainstay The Waiting Room, The Full Nelson has a similarly animal-free ethos but still serves up artery-clogging fodder that eschews any vegan cliche.

The staff may look like theyd wield brass knuckles at any misbehaving patrons, but theyre really cuddly little plush pandas who will happily guide you through your meat-free feast. The Colonel Burger - crispy coated chicken filet covered in garlic buffalo sauce with lemon and black pepper mayo - is finger-lickin good. Their cocktails, meanwhile, are some of the best weve sampled in SE. Theres some serious meatless magic going on here, and were all about it.

tip.text:
If you think being vegan is being healthy, then think again. Cookies & Scream is basically food porn for your vegan and gluten-free friends - serving opulent indulgences like peanut butter brownie milkshakes, ice cream sandwiches, as well as a range of cakes, pies and cookies. Having made the move from Camden to Holloway Road, they're dominating the treat scene in these parts.

We recommend the espresso shake, a contraption so creamy we genuinely dont understand how its vegan. Pair it with a cookie sandwich: two giant chocolate chip cookies sandwiched together with a thick lashing of vanilla frosting, and oh mama, veganism never tasted so guuuud.

tip.text:
One look through the neon pink glow of this two-storey vegan and organic Shoreditch hangout should be enough for you to know if it's for you. From the fluorescent hue, to the spiritual-skater-punk menu design, to the 50s Americana posters - the aesthetic is a hot mess of different styles, but at the end of the day, it all kinda works together in its brashness.

The menu is a similar story - a sprawling list of vegan dishes loosely under the umbrella of 'street food' with geographical influences ranging from South America, to the U.S, to India to Asia. Usually this would be a turn off, but once again, it all kinda works. The tacos in particular were delicious and convincing in their meatiness (chorizo in one and duck in the other); the sauerkraut dog was another highlight, with a peppery hit of mustard sitting nicely on sweet onions and brioche.

Cocktails, kimchi fries, noodles, cashew ice-cream, rich chocolate milkshakes - theres so much going on here and, while none of it is particularly subtle, its mostly all very tasty. The only misstep we had was the mac 'n' cheese that was almost inedibly salty. This place is definitely not for everyone, but those that are on board will love it, we thinks.
